Comment: This move looked strange the first time I saw it, but attacking d5.
So I'm thinking black may Fianchetto his bishop, but I have been fooled here before. I am wondering if black will move d5 and cause me to change plans.
Normally, I would move g3 and prepare my fortress, but I'm suspicious of a d5 pawn move, which I am not sure how to handle, so I take the initiative. I do really prefer to be on the assertive side.
Reducing the chance of a black Bd4 queen threat and preparing the castle.
Now that is a nice looking pawn chain black has. My pawns look a little weak.
Remedied the weak pawns. I like this configuration as well. Opens up both sides. However, the rear pawn requires constant defense with those pesky knights roaming about.
Additional defense of the knight and opening up the possibility of the long castle. Although with the black pawn chain, I don't think I'll castle queen side.
Temporary fix for the growing pressure on d4.
Well, I did say temporary. White queen is not thrilled about that, but I guess it's to be expected.
Didn't like blocking in my LSB, but I thought the black Kd4 move would not be fun either.
Not sure what Rb8 signaled. Black b5 to threaten queen? ... or a future LSB move?
Not sure what this is called, but looks like he pinned my knight.
Want to cover  my bishop so I can move the knight to discourage black's Nd4 (which I really think he wants at this point). However, my b2 pawn looks a bit helpless.
b5 appears imminent. Must move queen, must move queen.
